<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Open Data Institute</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#4f81bd; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-bottom:4pt"><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:26pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Written evidence from the </span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:26pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Open Data Institute</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:26pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> [OD0</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:26pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">9]</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Open data is important because it is the most effective way of putting information in the hands of those who can best use it. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Open data policies can be used to increase government transparency and accountability, foster innovation and economic growth, and to support more effective and efficient public services.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The UK has a justifiable reputation as a world leader in open data and has obtained a first mover advantage. The Open Data Institute (ODI) was set-up by the government to catalyse the creation of new economic value from open data. Just a year old, ODI is an open data success story that </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">19 </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">other</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> countries</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> are looking to emulate. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">However there is a danger, having set the early pace, that the Government’s sights are now set too low. The UK risks being overtaken as other countries like the US, France, Denmark and Australia forge ahead.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The Government’s Open Data Strategy, which stems from commitments in the Coalition Agreement to greater transparency, is primarily focused on the publication of more data. This strategy needs to mature rapidly along the lines recommended by the recent Shakespeare Review.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">In some areas, the Government has made great strides in opening up more data. In other important areas, the Government’s open data policies have not been seen through. Public-sector organisations are unwilling to lose direct revenue by making data that is currently charged for available for free. However well regulated, licensing public sector information on commercial terms necessarily restricts its use, curtails innovation and distorts competitive markets downstream.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The benefits of open data to government itself have not been fully realised. There are potentially important efficiency savings to be made from using open data. Starting to estimate those savings would provide the basis of the business case for more decisive action towards more open data. The benefits of open data include enabling external collaboration to increase data quality, efficiencies in reducing duplication of effort and savings through not having to pay the private sector for information that government holds.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">There is a capability gap within the civil service around using and publishing open data.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Statisticians are vitally important for opening up data, and those engaged in open data have a lot to learn from them. But their outputs are currently focused on people rather than programs. Re-users need access to </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">anonymised</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> versions of the underlying data.</span></li></ul><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">1. Why is open data important?</span></h1><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">For government, </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">publishing </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">open data is important in three ways:</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">by being open with its own data, government demonstrates </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">transparency</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">accountability</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">, which aids public </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">trust</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and increases </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">involvement</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> in the democratic process</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 44.54pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">by publishing and requiring the publication of open data that can be used to deliver public services, government can become more </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">efficient</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">, create a </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">level playing field</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">new models</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> for service delivery and make </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">data-driven decisions</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 45.53pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">by engendering a climate in which open data is shared by organisations, including government itself, government supports </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">innovation</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> in the form of both </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">new enterprises</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and greater efficiency and effectiveness for </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">existing businesses</span></li></ol><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Open data can be maintained in collaboration, by anyone, not just government. Government can benefit from the open data published by other </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> without the legal and financial barriers inherent in closed data.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">2. Why does the Government need an open data strategy?</span></h1><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">An economy needs information to operate efficiently. Government needs to ensure that the economy’s information needs are met. It therefore needs to take a strategic view of the nation’s information infrastructure, including which data the government collects and how it is shared.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">There is an on-going tension in how government data is shared. It can be treated as a public good. It can be provided on a cost-recovery basis. Or it can be managed commercially, providing a return on investment to the Treasury. Government needs a coherent data strategy to resolve these tensions, and the role of open data (data provided as a public good to maximise its benefit) should be central to that strategy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> Government has pursued parallel and contradictory policy objectives with open data. The first has been to aggressively move towards open data by default, setting up various bodies, groups, teams and processes to take that agenda forward. Expectations have been raised and some good progress has been made. The second has been to vigorously defend the status-quo of charging for government data, either for cost-recovery or commercially, which has held sway over the last 15 years. This is despite the growing evidence base that shows the economic benefits of open data and that, </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">owever well regulated, licensing public sector information on commercial terms necessarily restricts its use, curtails innovation and distort</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> competitive markets downstream.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The tension between the Government’s two policy approaches has increased. As a result the government lacks a truly coherent strategy for open data.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Ref239771050"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">To illustrate some of the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">tensions</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and contradictions in the Government’s approach, it created </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Open Data User Group (ODUG) to advise it on its </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">prioritisation</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> of open data releases. ODUG argued strongly for the creation and maintenance of an Open National Address Dataset, using data from the Postcode Address File (PAF), as national information infrastructure that would have wide ranging benefits for the public and private sector alike. The difficulty of separating PAF from Royal Mail as part of its </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">privatisation</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> means that PAF will now move into private hands, regardless of the benefits of PAF being open data. (A similar scenario in The Netherlands resulted in their Government fighting an EU court case to buy back postcode data to create an open address data asset as part of a </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> of efficiency savings for the public sector.)</span></a></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">A coherent open data strategy should:</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">cover open data as part of a wider strategy on sharing and using data, including in response to FOI requests, with individuals about themselves (</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Midata</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">) and in secure ways for research purposes</span></li></ol><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ensure that government collects the data that it and wider society needs, and handles this data in a responsible way that maximises its long-term utility, including by publishing it as open data</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 45.53pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">develop business models that can support the publication of open data, by seeing open data as a </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">public</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> good that can be maintained through collaboration between the government, businesses and citizens</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">commit the Government Digital Service (GDS) to develop a world-class data publishing platform for the public sector to use, as part of GOV.UK</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ensure that government itself benefits from open data publication, by equipping civil servants with the skills they need to make best use of available open data</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 42.87pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.33pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">reach beyond the government's own publication of data, including embedding open data into government's procurement process, to encourage a growing capability around the use of open data within the UK, to provide UK businesses with an advantage in this growing field</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">3. What should the Government’s aims be for the release of open data?</span></h1><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">In its publication of open data, the Government should aim to:</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">publish open reference data to a high quality</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">commit to long-term publication of open data so that others can rely on its availability</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 45.53pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">make it easy to discover relevant and important open data</span></li></ol><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The Open Data Institute’s Open Data Certificate helps assess the quality of </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">open data releases and aids prioritisation in improving publication. We recommend aiming for the Expert level of the Certificate for reference data, and for the Standard level of the Certificate for other open data, such as statistics.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">a. Are the Government’s stated key outcomes in its Open Data Strategy the right ones?</span></h2><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The Government’s strategy has been to stimulate a range of activities around open data, with a focus on publication. These are all necessary, but are not sufficient to maximise the benefits that the government could realise from open data.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> This strategy needs to mature rapidly along the lines recommended by the recent Shakespeare Review.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The Government created </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">the Open Data Institute (ODI)</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> to support the publication and reuse of open data, and to build the evidence base for the use of open data</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">. ODI has been successful as a convening point for large and small businesses, </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">startups</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">, academia and government, around open data. It </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">is also sparking</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> the creation of ODI nodes </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">in 19 countries </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">across the world.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> The ODI has provided support for the UK’s use of open data and established the UK as a leader in the field.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The Government formed the Open Data User Group (ODUG) to provide the voice of a wide range of data </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">reusers</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> back into government. As outlined in paragraph </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">, ODUG’s recommendations are not always listened to. As the Government goes forwards, it needs to ensure that it hears the voices of data re-users who are exploring new business models and modes of operation, not just those that wish to preserve the status-quo.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Departmental</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> Open Data Strategies are mainly concerned with identifying new data to be released.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> They are naturally focused on data strategies that are of benefit to the individual department’s objectives. What is needed in addition is a larger strategic view for the nation’s information infrastructure.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">We would also like to see a greater focus on:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">building capability within government for using open data in support of public sector activities</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">using open data to drive efficiency savings</span></li></ol></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">4. How can those engaged in open data, and those engaged in producing government statistics work together effectively to produce new data?</span></h1><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Government statisticians are experts at working with data to produce summaries and reports that can be understood within and outside government. Those publishing open data should adopt those responsible publishing practices adhered to by statisticians, particularly around documentation, quality assurance and statistical disclosure controls (</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">anonymisation</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">).</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Statisticians are often the maintainers of core reference data, as these code lists are used when creating statistics. They, as well as re-users of open data, benefit </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">from core reference data, particularly from other departments and public-sector organisations, being available as open data.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The next tranche of useful open data will come from applying statistical techniques over large or personal datasets that cannot be directly shared. Government statisticians are ideally placed to</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">create these new datasets</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">. An example would be school catchment areas derived from the National Pupil Database.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The open data community could work with government statisticians to develop practices that make statistical releases more re-usable as data</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">5. How can more statistics and administrative data of all kinds become more freely available?</span></h1><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">There are four methods that would make statistics and administrative data more accessible:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Publish the results of statistical analyses as data (for example in spreadsheets), rather than embedding them as tables within documents.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Provide access to low-level data rather than high-level summaries. Rather than releasing multiple spreadsheets containing different summaries of the same underlying data, provide the underlying data itself, or data at as low an aggregation as feasible while preserving statistical disclosure controls.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 32.33pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Create a routine publication schedule that reflects the frequency of changes to the underlying data. This enables re-users to create applications that more accurately reflect the available information.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Make the data more easily findable by those who are interested in the topic area. Underlying data should be linked to from reports and the latest releases should be referenced from policy pages on GOV.UK.</span></li></ol></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">6. Is open data presented well and of adequate quality?</span></h1><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">a. Are the formats of the data being published accessible, useable and understandable to the public?</span></h2><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">It is important to recognise that there are two types of audience for open data:</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The general public prefer data that is published in formats that they can open as spreadsheets. They will generally perform only rudimentary analyses over and above those already carried out on the data (such as graphing or mapping it). They will generally want information about that data to be available in the same spreadsheet as the data itself.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Developers prefer data that is published in formats they can read programmatically. They will be interested in combining different datasets together, accessing individual records on demand, and performing complex analyses over large datasets. They usually want documentation about the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">data to be separate from the data itself.</span></li></ol><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The majority of statistical data is published to cater to the general public rather than developers. While it may be accessible, usable and understandable to the public, the way in which it is published makes it harder to use for developers. If the data is valuable, developers will find ways to extract and use it; using formats like Excel spreadsheets raise the barrier for developer reuse, as do</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> changing </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">data</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> formats</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> over a series of releases</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">b. What metadata is needed to make releases useful?</span></h2><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Metadata serves two purposes</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">, both of which are necessary for useful releases</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">machine-readable metadata</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> makes it easier to search for data; this metadata needs to focus on things like date of release, temporal and spatial coverage and the subject area of the data</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 46.21pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">human-readable metadata</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> makes it easier for people to understand how to interpret the data and can include descriptions, provenance and quality issues, commitments to particular release cycles and information about how to receive further support</span></li></ol><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The metadata that's required for a given dataset depends on the type of data that's included within the dataset. There is a core set of metadata that is recommended by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in the form of </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ata </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Catalog</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> Vocabulary (DCAT)</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> but more specific metadata can be useful. For example, it's useful to know the details of the dimensions and measures included in statistical data. When data is published as linked data, on the other hand, metadata can provide information such as URL templates and SPARQL endpoints.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The question of which standard set of metadata to use for data releases is the topic of a current Open Standards Challenge</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:normal">c.</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> Who will use the data released?</span></h2><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Open data should be used by:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">the public sector – it is more efficient to make data generall</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">y available to everyone than to create dedicated channels between individual public-sector organisations</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">the private sector – both established and new companies benefit from open government data; the ODI currently hosts </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">nine</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">start-ups who use open data to create new products and services</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 32.33pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">the third sector – to aid in planning</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> their activities, including disaster response,</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and to hold the government to account</span></li></ol></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">7. How successful has the Government’s Open Data initiative been in changing behaviour in the Civil Service and wider public sector?</span></h1><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">There has been </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">substantial</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> progress within government </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">since the Coalition Agreement that sets out the Government policy for transparency, including a number of open data commitments</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> Open data can be a tool for more than transparency and accountability, and a wider appreciation of the role of open data has evolved more recently, particularly focusing on economic benefits.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">In our experience, there is fairly wide recognition for the open data agenda (though sometimes based on misunderstandings about the meaning of open data). Many public-sector organisations publish open data on a routine basis and are keen to investigate what more they could do.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">There are several gaps where the government needs to develop capability:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">understanding how to use open data publication to further departmental goals, so that it becomes embedded into existing processes and is used to </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">realise efficiency gains</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">understanding how to consume and reuse open data published by other organisations, improving data literacy more generally, so that government takes advantage of data that is now available</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; margin:8pt 0pt 8pt 32.33pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">technical support for publishing open data beyond static spreadsheets, particularly as APIs or database dumps that are more useful for open data </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">reusers</span></li></ol></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">8. Which datasets are the most important?</span></h1><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The most important datasets are those that can be re</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">used by the most people and in the most ways. We emphasise core reference data because that data is, by definition, referenced across multiple datasets and therefore makes it possible to combine other datasets together in interesting ways. Geographical data is particularly important because so many datasets refer to some aspect of geography.</span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">a. What are the best examples of data being made open and resultant benefits to business or society?</span></h2><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The release of NHS Prescription data led to the identification of a potential £200m/year saving for the NHS if doctors prescribed generic </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">statins</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> rather than proprietary </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">statins</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">. This analysis is now being taken forward to </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">investigate integrating</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> prescription advice into the systems used within GP surgeries</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> and pharmacies</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The publication of the UK’s legislation as open data has resulted in the development of a new collaborative model for keeping legislation up to date, improving access to legislation for the public and potentially saving government money in licensing fees to private-sector legislation publishers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Transport data is now much more widely available than it was, particularly in London, and is being made good use of in applications that help people to locate </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">bikes through Barclays Cycle Hire</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> or anticipate the arrival of the next bus.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#345a8a; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">9. How effective is the work being undertaken by the Cabinet Office to monitor the progress of Departments in publishing their agreed datasets?</span></h1><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The data.gov.uk website should act as a monitoring platform for adherence to governmental and departmental open data targets. It does this effectively for some datasets, such as spending data</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">The Cabinet Office should be assessing open data releases in the context of a thought-through national information infrastructure rather than the parochial goals of individual departments.</span></li><li style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:8pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">To give confidence to re-users of government data, releases should be measured against the ODI’s Open Data Certificates. These assess all aspects of open data releases, including legal, technical, practical and social considerations that are important for on-going reuse.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> http://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-dcat/</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> http://standards.data.gov.uk/challenge/describing-and-sharing-our-information</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> http://data.gov.uk/data/openspending-report/index</span></p></body></html>